{
  "text": "It should be noted that a number of different cadherin subtypes with distinct adhesion specificity are differentially expressed in postnatal brains (Suzuki, S.C., T. Inoue, and M. Takeichi, manuscript in preparation). Because of their region-specific distribution and binding specificity, it is likely that each cadherin subtype is used for the specific association of limited sets of neurons and that catenins ubiquitously support the cadherin function. N-cadherin is one of such neuronal cadherins, which is expressed by restricted components of the chicken visual circuit [CITATION_1] . Our present observation showed that N-cadherin is specifically localized at tectal and PT junctions in the midbrain stem, supporting the above idea.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "21774530"
